\begin_layout Standard

\size small
Once you were young.
 No matter how old we may be, all of us were once young.
 We looked at the world through truly fresh eyes, felt it as fully and intensely
 as anyone ever could.
 When we loved, it was the happiest days we had ever known.
 When we were hurt, it was the greatest tragedy we had ever felt.
 And the world shined with possibility.
 We all thought we had a way to change the world, embracing it with all
 our hearts.
 We looked to our heroes and told ourselves "I can do that too".
 It seemed that if only we were given our chance, we could make the world
 better.
 That the pains of the world we felt so strongly were something we could
 overcome...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
...
 we believed.
 We all once believed.
 And yet, when you look at the world around you today...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
One day, you saw a man huddling in a corner, covered in all too old rags
 when you came out of the supermarket.
 So many people passed him, looking at him sadly then turning away.
 You could see the desperation on his face.
 You couldn't bear it...
 You give him what cash you had, and a change of clothes.
 It wasn't enough.
 You knew it wasn't enough...
 Not if you were the only one helping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
That night, you confided in your old friend from kindergarten.
 Who you had always relied on, who had always stood by your side back then.
 ...
 and yet, this time, she frowned.
 She asked you if you really thought that money would really change anything,
 or if he would just use it to buy beer.
 She told you she was worried about how you would live through college if
 you kept doing this.
 She told you that you should let people like that go.
 That night, you cried yourself to sleep.
 Why couldn't you just be like them?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
One day, you told your parents that you wanted to be a writer instead of
 a doctor.
 They told you that you didn't really want that.
 That you wouldn't ever be popular anyway, and you'd be starving on the
 street.
 They told you that if you threw away your life like that, they wouldn't
 help you anymore.
 They told you to stop being stuck in a dream.
 You weren't sure what else you expected...
 everywhere you went, there were so many people who had given up on hoping
 so long ago.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
At least, this time was different.
 That night, you logged into the same chat room you found a few weeks ago.
 One full of people who understand your pains.
 They got it.
 They also still believed.
 They also still dreamed.
 And they comforted you.
 Showed you a way forward.
 Reassured you in the path you chose...
 They told you that it was okay to be you.
 This time, you had less reason to cry.
 Even if you still did.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
One day, you saw a boy crying in the toy aisle, clinging tightly to a stuffed
 animal he wanted.
 But his parents wouldn't have any of that.
 Because boys weren't supposed to like things like that.
 Because boys weren't supposed to cry.
 Because that is not how the world was supposed to be.
 And so many onlookers walked by, even watched with sneers on their faces.
 You couldn't tell who they even were sneering at, the mother or you.
 It didn't matter.
 Nobody helped.
 Nobody else helped.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
...
 but you tried anyway.
 Even as they dragged him away as they called you terrible names.
 He wasn't crying as much anymore.
 ...
 maybe, just maybe.
 You showed him that he wasn't alone in the world.
 Just like your friends once did for you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
You never could give up, no matter how hard you tried.
 No matter how much everyone around you told you to save yourself, that
 you were naive and only hurting yourself.
 You couldn't stop caring.
 You couldn't stop believing.
 You couldn't stop trying.
 You couldn't forgive yourself if you did.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size small
And that...
 is what makes you a Luminous.
 Not the shining magic you wield, but the simple fact you could never stop
 dreaming of a better world.
 
\end_layout

